              min=0.200000, max=0.714286

  From Claim A: n·H(T) = Σ_v H(T-v) + 2 Σ_C L(C)·μ(C)

  So H(T) = [Σ_v H(T-v) + 2 Σ_C L(C)·μ(C)] / n

  This IS a recurrence, but it depends on the CYCLE STRUCTURE
  of T, not just the H-values of subtournaments.

  The '2' in 2μ(C) is the OCF evaluation point x=2.
  If we used x=3, we'd get a '3' factor instead.

======================================================================
PART 5: THE (2,3) DUALITY IN DELETION-CONTRACTION
======================================================================

I(CG, x) satisfies deletion-contraction on the conflict graph:
  I(G, x) = I(G-v, x) + x·I(G-N[v], x)

At x=2: I(G, 2) = I(G-v, 2) + 2·I(G-N[v], 2)
At x=3: I(G, 3) = I(G-v, 3) + 3·I(G-N[v], 3)

The RATIO of the 'contraction' terms is 3/2.
This is the same 3/2 that appears everywhere!

For an isolated vertex v (no neighbors in CG):
  I(G, x) = I(G-v, x) + x·I(G, x)  ... no, N[v]={v}
  I(G, x) = I(G-v, x) + x·I(G-{v}, x) ... but G-{v} and G-N[v] differ
  Actually: I(G, x) = I(G-v, x) + x·I(G-N[v], x)
  For isolated v: N[v] = {v}, so G-N[v] = G-v
  I(G, x) = I(G-v, x) + x·I(G-v, x) = (1+x)·I(G-v, x)

  At x=2: factor = 1+2 = 3
  At x=3: factor = 1+3 = 4

  Each isolated vertex in CG contributes a factor of (1+x).
  For H = I(CG, 2): each isolated cycle multiplies H by 3.
  For I₃ = I(CG, 3): each isolated cycle multiplies I₃ by 4.

  The RATIO of multiplicative factors: 4/3 = (1+3)/(1+2)
  But we said the ratio is 3/2 earlier!
  The 3/2 ratio is for the ADDITIVE part (contraction term).
  The 4/3 ratio is for the MULTIPLICATIVE part (isolated vertex).

  BOTH ratios involve 2 and 3:
  3/2 = 3/2
  4/3 = (3+1)/(2+1)

  And 3/2 × 4/3 = 2.  Full circle: back to the root!

======================================================================
PART 6: HOW 7 AND 8 APPEAR AS RECURRENCE PARAMETERS
======================================================================

At n=7 (=2³-1):
  The 7-nacci root is φ₇ = 1.99196... ≈ 2 - 1/128 = 2 - 2^{-7}
  The 7-cycle first appears in tournaments
  The Jacobsthal at level k=4 has denominator 7

At n=8 (=2³):
  The 8-nacci root is φ₈ = 1.99603... ≈ 2 - 1/256 = 2 - 2^{-8}
  First cross-level cycle packing (3+5=8)
  Q = (H²-Pf²)/8: the divisor 8 = 2³ first matters

The 7-step and 8-step recurrences (Families B/C at k=7,8):

  k=7 k-nacci: f(n) = f(n-1) + ... + f(n-7)
    Dominant root: 1.9919641966
    Gap to 2: 8.0358033950e-03

  k=8 k-nacci: f(n) = f(n-1) + ... + f(n-8)
    Dominant root: 1.9960311797
    Gap to 2: 3.9688202646e-03

  k=7 weighted: f(n) = f(n-1) + 2f(n-2) + ... + 64f(n-7)
    Dominant root: 2.9311424638
    Gap to 3: 6.8857536246e-02

  k=8 weighted: f(n) = f(n-1) + 2f(n-2) + ... + 128f(n-8)
    Dominant root: 2.9560974219
    Gap to 3: 4.3902578069e-02

THE JACOBSTHAL CONNECTION:
  J₁₂(n) = (4^n - (-3)^n) / 7
  The denominator 7 = 2·4 - 1 = 2k-1 for k=4

  So 7 appears as a JACOBSTHAL DENOMINATOR,
  and denominators ↔ cycle lengths (3, 5, 7, ...)

  The 7-cycle is the first cycle that REQUIRES n≥7 vertices.
  It's the first cycle beyond the 'single Jacobsthal level' regime.

  When a 7-cycle coexists with a 3-cycle (at n≥10=7+3),
  or with another 3-cycle and a 5-cycle (at n≥15=7+3+5),
  the Jacobsthal levels couple through the conflict graph.

THE Q DIVISOR:
  Q(T) = (H(T)² - Pf(T)²) / 8
  Why 8? Because H² - Pf² = I(CG,2)² - det(I+2A)
  and det(I+2A) = 1 + 0 + 0 + 8c₃ + 16c₄ + ...
  The first non-trivial coefficient is at x³ with coefficient 8c₃.

  Why is the coefficient 8? Because:
  det(I+xA) = 1 + Σ_{k≥3} c_k · x^k
  c₃ = #{3-cycles}, and x³ = 2³ = 8 at x=2.
  So 8 = 2³ is the 'entry point' for cycle contributions.

======================================================================
PART 7: THE 10-11 INTERPOLATION IN RECURRENCE SPACE
======================================================================

POSITION OF 10 AND 11:

  Jacobsthal integer-root points: x = k(k-1)
  k=3: x=6,  root=3
  k=4: x=12, root=4

  At x=10: root ≈ 3.702
  At x=11: root ≈ 3.854

  These are (10-6)/(12-6) = 4/6 = 2/3 and (11-6)/(12-6) = 5/6
  of the way from k=3 to k=4.

  THE 2/3 AGAIN! x=10 is EXACTLY 2/3 of the way between
  consecutive integer-root Jacobsthal levels!

  Exact fractions:
  (10-6)/(12-6) = 4/6 = 2/3
  (11-6)/(12-6) = 5/6 = 5/6

  So 10 is at position 2/3 between x=6 and x=12,
  and 11 is at position 5/6.

  The root interpolation:
  root(x=10) = 3.701562, position in [3,4]: 0.701562 = 47/67
  root(x=11) = 3.854102, position in [3,4]: 0.854102 = 41/48

  10 = 2 + 8 = x_OCF + 2³
  This means: I(CG, 10) = I(CG, 2 + 8)

  Taylor expansion of I(CG, x) around x=2:
    I(CG, 2+δ) = I(CG, 2) + δ·I'(CG, 2) + δ²·I''(CG, 2)/2 + ...
                = H + δ·(α₁ + 4α₂ + ...) + ...

  At δ=8: I(CG, 10) = H + 8·I'(CG, 2) + 32·I''(CG, 2) + ...

  Similarly, 11 = 3 + 8 = x_topo + 2³
  I(CG, 11) = I(CG, 3 + 8) ← Taylor around x=3!
    = I₃ + 8·I'(CG, 3) + 32·I''(CG, 3) + ...

  So I(CG, 10) and I(CG, 11) encode DERIVATIVES of I at 2 and 3,
  weighted by powers of 8 = 2³!

  For degree-2 case (n ≤ 8, typically):
    I(CG, x) = 1 + α₁x + α₂x²
    I(CG, 2) = 1 + 2α₁ + 4α₂ = H
    I(CG, 3) = 1 + 3α₁ + 9α₂ = I₃
    I(CG, 10) = 1 + 10α₁ + 100α₂
    I(CG, 11) = 1 + 11α₁ + 121α₂

  Relations:
    I(10) - I(2) = 8α₁ + 96α₂ = 8(α₁ + 12α₂)
    I(11) - I(3) = 8α₁ + 112α₂ = 8(α₁ + 14α₂)

    Both divisible by 8!
    (I(10) - I(2)) / 8 = α₁ + 12α₂
    (I(11) - I(3)) / 8 = α₁ + 14α₂

    Subtracting: [(I(11)-I(3)) - (I(10)-I(2))] / 8 = 2α₂
    So: α₂ = [(I(11) - I(10)) - (I(3) - I(2))] / 16

    And: α₁ = (I(10) - I(2))/8 - 12α₂

  THE 10-11 PAIR EXTRACTS (α₁, α₂) just like the 2-3 pair does,
  but shifted by 8!

======================================================================
PART 8: NESTED RECURRENCE STRUCTURE
    (2,3) → (7,8) → (10,11)
======================================================================

LEVEL 1: (2,3) — The fundamental Vandermonde extraction
  I(2), I(3) → α₁, α₂ via Vandermonde:
    α₂ = (2·I(3) - 3·I(2) + 1) / 6 = (2I₃ - 3H + 1) / 6
    α₁ = (I(2) - 1 - 4α₂) / 2 = (H - 1 - 4α₂) / 2

  The denominator 6 = 2·3 (product of the pair!)

LEVEL 2: (7,8) — The cross-level threshold
  At n=8, α₂ splits into α₂^{33} (both 3-cycles) and α₂^{35} (3+5)
  I(2) and I(3) can't separate these — need I(6) or I(7)
  The pair (7,8) tells us when to expect this complexity.

LEVEL 3: (10,11) — The shifted Vandermonde
  I(10) = I(2 + 8), I(11) = I(3 + 8)
  These are the I(2) and I(3) values 'shifted by 8=2³'
  (I(10) - H) / 8 and (I(11) - I₃) / 8 give higher-order info

THE NESTING:
  At level 1, (2,3) extracts α₁, α₂ from H and I₃
  At level 3, (10,11) = (2+8, 3+8) extracts the SAME α₁, α₂
  but through a different linear combination — providing a
  CONSISTENCY CHECK on the α values.

  In fact, ANY consecutive pair (x, x+1) with x ≡ 0 mod 2
  or x ≡ 2 mod 3 gives a Vandermonde extraction of (α₁, α₂).
  But (2,3), (10,11), (7,8) are special because they also
  encode the hierarchical structure of cycle packing.

======================================================================
PART 9: THE RECURRENCE LATTICE DIAGRAM
======================================================================

               1 (identity)
              / \
             2   3  (the two keys)
            / \ / \
           4   6   9  (2², 2·3, 3²)
          / \ / \
         7   8   12  (2³-1, 2³, 2²·3)
          \ / \ /
          10   11  (2+8, 3+8)

  Each node n defines:
  1. A k-nacci recurrence with root → 2
  2. A weighted k-nacci recurrence with root → 3
  3. A Jacobsthal evaluation I(CG, n) or I(CG, n(n-1))
  4. A tournament size where new packing structures appear

  The lattice is organized by the TWO operations:
  • 'doubling': n → 2n (multiplication by 2)
  • 'tripling': n → 3n (multiplication by 3)
  which generate the 2-3 lattice Z[1/6].

======================================================================
FINAL SUMMARY: EVERYTHING IS A RECURRENCE
======================================================================

  RECURRENCE          | ROOT(S)     | RATE     | KEY NUMBER
  --------------------+-------------+----------+-----------
  Fibonacci           | φ, -1/φ     | —        | 1
  Jacobsthal (x=2)   | 2, -1       | —        | 2
  Jacobsthal (x=6)   | 3, -2       | —        | 3
  Jacobsthal (x=12)  | 4, -3       | —        | 7 (denom)
  k-nacci (any k)    | → 2         | 1/2      | 2
  w-k-nacci (any k)  | → 3         | 2/3      | 3
  I(CG, x) del-con   | 1+x         | —        | 3 (at x=2)
  H deletion          | 2-weighted  | —        | 2
  Q = (H²-Pf²)/8    | —           | —        | 8 = 2³
  α₁ mod 2 tower     | 2-adic      | —        | 2
  b₀ mod 3 tower     | 3-adic      | —        | 3

  2 controls: counting (H), convergence (k-nacci → 2),
              divisibility (H odd), deletion weight

  3 controls: topology (b₀), convergence (w-k-nacci → 3),
              isolated vertex weight (1+x=3), CRT bridge

  7 = 2³-1: last pure (single-level) tournament size,
            Jacobsthal denominator, Mersenne prime

  8 = 2³:   first cross-level, Q divisor, packing threshold

  10 = 2+8: shifted counting point, 2/3 interpolation
  11 = 3+8: shifted topology point, first perfect α₃ packing

  'If one understands 2 and 3, one has the keys to the universe.'
  2 and 3 are the eigenvalues. 7 and 8 are the transition.
  10 and 11 are the interleaving. Everything else follows.

Done.
